		<section>
			<section.front>
				<doc.title toc-guid="I03014f37829b11e9b500ff79cbddef67">
					<head parent="doc.title">
						<label.name>§ </label.name>
						<label.designator>15:92.</label.designator>
						<headtext>Plans for individuals with regular income—Conversion from Chapter 7 to Chapter 13 is tempered by good faith: <ital>Marrama v. Citizens Bank of Massachusetts</ital>[<footnote.reference refid="Idf1aec30c34711eb9819b48b4c940e6a">1</footnote.reference>]</headtext>
					</head>
				</doc.title>
			</section.front>
			<section.body>
				<para>
					<paratext>
						Subsection
						[<footnote.reference refid="Idf1aec31c34711eb9819b48b4c940e6a">2</footnote.reference>] Any other interested party who asks for conversion of the case is hedged with limitations which “the court may” examine.[
						<footnote.reference refid="Idf1aec32c34711eb9819b48b4c940e6a">3</footnote.reference>] The House<page no="971"/> and Senate Committee <page no="972"/>Reports describe the “… one-time absolute right of conversion. …”
						which the debtor is given.
					</paratext>
				</para>
			</section.body>
		</section>
